In 2026, while the Differentiable Binarization (DB) algorithm remains a top-tier choice for real-time text detection due to its balance of speed and accuracy, several "stronger" and more specialized alternatives have emerged. 
The choice of "better" depends on whether you prioritize raw accuracy, handling complex documents, or processing speed. 
1. Stronger Detection-Focused Algorithms
These algorithms improve upon the standard DB approach by using more advanced architectures like Transformers or improved binarization techniques. 
DB++ (Improved DB): An evolution of the original DB algorithm that uses an Adaptive Scale Fusion (ASF) module to better handle text of varying sizes.
STARK & Mamba-based Detectors: Recent models utilizing the Mamba state space model or specialized Transformers have shown superior capability in modeling long-range dependencies, helping them identify text in extremely cluttered or distorted scenes where DB might fail.
CRAFT (Character Region Awareness for Text Detection): While often slower than DB, CRAFT is considered more "robust" for irregular or curved text because it detects individual characters rather than entire word blocks. 
2. Comprehensive AI-Based Solutions (End-to-End)
Modern systems have moved beyond simple "detection algorithms" to Intelligent Document Processing (IDP), which integrates detection and recognition into a single powerful workflow. 
Mistral OCR (Benchmark Leader): Launched in early 2025, this is currently cited as an industry benchmark for document understanding. It processes up to 2,000 pages per minute and handles complex tables, equations, and diverse fonts with higher precision than standalone DB-based systems.
TrOCR (Transformer-based OCR): An end-to-end model that does not require a separate detection step. It uses a Vision Transformer (ViT) to "see" and a language Transformer to "write," making it exceptionally strong for handwriting and high-quality document scanning.
Google Document AI & Azure AI Vision: These cloud services use "ensembles" of many models (including DB-like segmentation and Transformers) to achieve near-human accuracy on complex layouts like invoices and medical forms. 
3. Which One to Use?
Requirement 	Recommended Algorithm/System
Highest Speed	DB (Differentiable Binarization)
Best for Complex Forms	Mistral OCR or Google Document AI
Best for Handwriting	TrOCR or Azure AI Document Intelligence
Best for Irregular Shapes	CRAFT
Best Open Source Bundle	PaddleOCR (Uses a refined version of DB)




