In 2026, Mistral OCR is a state-of-the-art multimodal API known for its high cognition and document understanding capabilities. While it is highly efficient, it is primarily a commercial service accessed via API, though its capabilities can be tested for free on Le Chat. 
For high-speed, high-accuracy OCR that is absolutely free (open source) and specifically optimized for CPUs, the following models are the top choices in 2026:
1. PaddleOCR (PP-OCRv4/v5)
PaddleOCR remains the gold standard for open-source OCR due to its ultra-lightweight architecture and superior accuracy on both CPUs and GPUs. 
Speed & Efficiency: The "Mobile" versions of its models are less than 10MB and are designed for real-time inference on mobile devices and standard CPUs.
Accuracy: It consistently outperforms Tesseract in character and word accuracy, especially on complex layouts like tables and multi-language documents.
License: Apache 2.0 (Free for commercial use). 
2. Tesseract 5.x
Tesseract is the most mature CPU-first OCR engine. While it lacks the deep learning "contextual" smarts of newer models, its raw speed on a CPU is often unmatched. 
Speed: It can be up to 6x faster than deep learning-based models on a standard CPU for high-volume batch processing of clean, printed text.
Optimization: Using the tessdata_fast models (8-bit integer versions) provides a significant speed boost with only a minor trade-off in accuracy.
License: Apache 2.0. 
3. Docling (by IBM)
Released as a major open-source tool, Docling is optimized for converting complex documents into lightweight formats like Markdown. 
CPU Advantage: It is designed to be efficient on commodity hardware, making it excellent for processing digital-born PDFs and simple scanned documents into structured text without requiring a high-end GPU.
License: MIT/Apache variants (Free/Open Source). 
4. Moondream2
Moondream2 is a tiny, compact vision-language model (under 2 billion parameters) specifically built for resource-constrained "edge" devices like laptops and mobile phones. 
Performance: It provides real-time document scanning on CPUs and has improved its ability to read forms and tables significantly.
Size: At roughly 1GB, it fits easily into standard memory without needing massive server clusters. 
